SIMPLE: infection
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infection
<hw>In*fec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>infection</ets>, L. <ets>infectio</ets> a dyeing.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of infecting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a strict order against coming to those pits, and that
was only to prevent <qex>infection</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>De
Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which infects, or causes the communicated
disease; any effluvium, miasm, or pestilential matter by which an
infectious disease is caused.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And that which was still worse, they that did thus break out
spread the <qex>infection</qex> further by their wandering about with
the distemper upon them.</q> <rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The state of being infected; the condition of
suffering from an infectious disease; contamination by morbific
particles; the result of infecting influence; a prevailing disease;
epidemic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The danger was really very great, the <qex>infection</qex> being
so very violent in London.</q> <rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which taints or corrupts morally; <as>as, the
<ex>infection</ex> of vicious principles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was her chance to light⟦br⟧
Amidst the gross <qex>infections</qex> of those times.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Contamination by illegality, as in
cases of contraband goods; implication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Sympathetic communication of like qualities or
emotions; influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through all her train the soft <qex>infection</qex> ran.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mankind are gay or serious by <qex>infection</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A localized area of tissue which is inflamed by
growth of microorganisms; <as>as, he has an <ex>infection</ex> in his
finger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Infection</er>, <er>Contagion</er>.</syn>
<usage> -- <xex>Infection</xex> is often used in a definite and limited
sense of the transmission of affections without direct contact of
individuals or immediate application or introduction of the morbific
agent, in contradistinction to <xex>contagion</xex>, which then implies
transmission by direct contact. <au>Quain</au>. See
<er>Contagious</er>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infectious</ent>⟦br⟧
